Quite simply as said here it will simply take longer to create the things @grelysian wants to make, and it'll be a longer road to ensure @grelysian and the team  have enough funds in a long-term situation.

https://t.co/MKbnpbSvNX

Not only do these things take time, but @grelysian spending time designing and creating merchandise and other longer term projects means they are unable to consistently make fine art drops for income. The fund was also intended to help provide some cushion.

The type of funding that would be needed is for continued legal expenses, the construction, manufacturing, and iteration of custom merchandise (where you interface directly with manufacturers - not like Printful or other on-demand services). These things cost money in USD.

Because of market conditions, it will not be fully possible to realize a true funding from the mint. Secondary is not reliable, although I do understand we will make some money it is not something we will know until it occurs, and therefore this was not factored in.

text: 11/12 So, was it worth spending all this time to create a fair allow list distribution between PREMINT, partner projects, and qualifying NFTs? Yes, we do think so, and we think our community will be better because of it.
10/12 Please note that the red flags and research methods were used universally across all PREMINT entries and during our manual review of partner project entries and qualifying NFTs.

9/12 Our team then completed a raffle in a random, tamper-proof way and pulled approximately 1000 wallets. These wallets were reviewed manually based on our red flags. This reduced the 1000 to our final public raffle allow list and a small waitlist.

8/12 Our team then manually reduced this list from 56k to about 25k using additional research based on our ‚Äúred flags‚Äù The data we reviewed was pulled directly from your premint entry. We reviewed patterns in this data set, and determined what would become our ‚Äúred flags.‚Äù
7/12 We partnered with @flipsidecrypto and @mulligan for a bulk of the review. Using on-chain data Flipside helped us narrow down our entries from 111k to about 56k.
6/12 Our team utilized similar methods to de-bot (remove invalid entries from bad actors trying to game the system) our PREMINT raffle as the @moonbirds team. We worked on this from May 1 - May 14.
5/12 We received 111,569 entries for our Premint raffle. (Yes we got heavily botted.) https://t.co/DUh05mlSwM
